[1] Molecular evidence for the presence of huanglongbing in Pakistan
[2] Greening tops canker as most feared disease for citrus growers in the US
******
[1] Molecular evidence for the presence of huanglongbing in Pakistan
Date: 29 March 2007
Source: Australasian Plant Disease Notes vol. 2 2007 [edited]
<http://www.publish.csiro.au/view/journals/dsp_journal_fulltext.cfm?nid=208&f=DN07019>

Citrus decline is widespread throughout Pakistan and is variously
attributed to orchard neglect, poor plant nutrition, water logging,
fungal diseases or nematodes. While these causes of decline can be
expected to affect citrus orchards in Pakistan, it is more likely
that the main cause of decline is due to a bacterial disease called
huanglongbing (HLB: also known as citrus greening) caused by the
bacterium _Candidatus_ Liberibacter asiaticus. The disease is
present in all of the countries neighbouring Pakistan, and in India
HLB has been reported to be present in all citrus-growing regions.
The presence of _Ca._ L. asiaticus in citrus orchards in the
North-West Frontier Province of Pakistan has been confirmed. Samples
of DNA extracted from leaves of putatively infected citrus plants and
from the vector of the disease, _Diaphorina citri_ (Asiatic citrus
psyllid), were subjected to analysis using PCR [polymerase chain
reaction] and produced DNA amplicons characteristic of this
bacterium. To confirm the exact nature of the pathogen, amplicons
were sequenced and the resulting data showed 100 percent identity
with published sequences of the _Ca._ L. asiaticus _rplKAJL-rpoBC_
operon.
This study is the first to provide molecular evidence for the
presence of _Ca._ L. asiaticus in Pakistan and future work will
determine the extent and occurrence of the disease as a first step
towards the overall management of HLB.
[Byline: Reference: S.N. Chohan et al. 2007, Australasian Plant
Disease Notes 2, 37-38]
--
